<module>
  <title><mark>the</mark> – definite article</title>
  <p>Simply put, there are four basic forms of the definite article in Gaelic –</p>
  <ol>
    <li>leniting <strong>an</strong></li>
    <li>non-leniting <strong>an</strong></li>
    <li><strong>na</strong></li>
    <li><strong>nan</strong></li>
  </ol>
  <p>These forms agree with the gender/number and case of the noun they specify as follows –</p>
  <table class="table w-auto">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <td></td><th>masculine</th><th>feminine</th><th>plural</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <th>nominative</th><td>non-leniting <strong>an</strong></td><td>leniting <strong>an</strong></td><td><strong>na</strong></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <th>dative</th><td>leniting <strong>an</strong></td><td>leniting <strong>an</strong></td><td><strong>na</strong></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <th>genitive</th><td>leniting <strong>an</strong></td><td><strong>na</strong></td><td><strong>nan</strong></td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>The precise realisation of each form of the Gaelic definite article depends on the phonological nature of the start of the following word –</p>
  <ul>
    <li>leniting <strong>an</strong> –
      <ul>
        <li>If the following word begins with <strong>p-</strong>, <strong>c-</strong>, <strong>b-</strong>, <strong>g-</strong>, <strong>m-</strong>, 
        the word is lenited and the form of the article changes to <strong>a’</strong>.</li>
        <li>If the following word begins with <strong>f-</strong>, the word is lenited.</li>
        <li>If the following word begins with <strong>s-</strong> followed by a vowel, <strong>-l-</strong>, <strong>-r-</strong> or <strong>-n-</strong>, 
        it is prefixed by <strong>t-</strong>.</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li>non-leniting <strong>an</strong> –
      <ul>
        <li>if the following word begins with a labial consonant (i.e. <strong>p-</strong>, <strong>b-</strong>, <strong>f-</strong>, <strong>m-</strong>), 
          the form of the article changes to <strong>am</strong></li>
        <li>if the following word begins with a vowel, it is prefixed by <strong>t-</strong></li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li><strong>na</strong> –
      <ul>
        <li>if the following word begins with a vowel, it is prefixed by <strong>h-</strong></li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li><strong>nan</strong> –
      <ul>
        <li>if the following word begins with a labial consonant (i.e. <strong>p-</strong>, <strong>b-</strong>, <strong>f-</strong>, <strong>m-</strong>), 
          the form of the article changes to <strong>nam</strong></li>
      </ul>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>Example paradigms –</p>
  <ul>
    <li>masculine nouns – <boxlink2 ref="#ainm">ainm</boxlink2>, 
      <boxlink2 ref="#balach">balach</boxlink2>, 
      <boxlink2 ref="#blaigeard">blaigeard</boxlink2>, 
      <boxlink2 ref="#broc">broc</boxlink2>, c, duine, eilean, fear, gille, i, loch, manach, neul, òran, p, reul, s, ubhal</li>
    <li>feminine nouns – <boxlink2 ref="#abhainn">abhainn</boxlink2>, 
      <boxlink2 ref="#buthaid">buthaid</boxlink2>, 
      <boxlink2 ref="#bliadhna">bliadhna</boxlink2>, <boxlink2 ref="#braiste">bràiste</boxlink2>,
      <boxlink2 ref="#caileag">caileag</boxlink2>, 
      <boxlink2 ref="#clach">clach</boxlink2>, làmh, sùil, </li>
  </ul>
  
  <box id="ainm">
    <title>ainm</title>
    <p><strong>ainm</strong> <en>name</en> is a masculine noun.</p>
    <table class="table w-auto">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <td></td><th>singular</th><th>plural</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <th>nominative</th><td><mark>an t-</mark>ainm <en>the name</en></td><td><mark>na h-</mark>ainmean <en>the names</en></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>dative</th><td>(leis) <mark>an</mark> ainm <en>(with) the name</en></td><td>(leis) <mark>na h-</mark>ainmean <en>(with) the names</en></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>genitive</th><td>(tùs) <mark>an</mark> ainm <en>the name’s (origin)</en></td><td>(tùs) <mark>nan</mark> ainmean <en>the names’ (origin)</en></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </box>
  
